{
  "texts": [
    "While deep neural networks have achieved significant progress in ED [10,24,30,33,35,44], they heavily rely on labeled data, which can be costly and time-consuming to obtain.",
    "Moreover, in real-world scenarios, new event types may emerge with limited available data, leading to poor performance in detecting these newly-emerged events.",
    "Thus, there is a need to transform the conventional supervised event detection task into a few-shot event detection (FSED) problem, which aims to detect new event types with limited data accurately.",
    "Most existing few-shot event detection (FSED) methods adopt a meta-learning paradigm [39] and generate N-way K-shot meta-tasks.",
    "For example, Table 1 shows a 3-way-2-shot FSED task with a support and query set."
  ]
}